window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>1>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : LOGARITHMS","question":"Given that log102 = 0.3010 and log103 = 0.4771, calculate without using mathematical tables or calculator, the values of:    Log1054    ** Leave your answer in four decimal places","images":[],"marking_scheme":"We are given,  Log102 = 0.3010 and Log 103 = 0.4771    Log1054 = Log10(27 \u00d7 2)  Log1033 + Log102  substituting  3(0.4771) + 0.3010  1.4313 + 0.3010 = 1.7323","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>1>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : LOGARITHMS","question":"Given that log102 = 0.3010 and log103 = 0.4771, calculate without using mathematical tables or calculator, the values of:  Log100.24     Leave your answer in four decimal places 'a.bcde'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Log100.24=Log10(24100)  Log1024 - Log10100  Log10(2 x 2 x 2 x 3) - Log10100  Log10(23 \u00d7 3) - Log10100  Log10(23 \u00d7 3) - Log10100  3Log102 + Log103 - 2Log1010  We knw that Log1010 = 1  \u21d2 3(0.3010) + 0.4771 - 2.0000  \u21d2 1.3801 - 2.000  \u21d2 -0.6199","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>2>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : LAWS OF INDICES","question":"Simplify135n*times9n-1\u00d727n+1","images":[],"marking_scheme":"135n\u00d79n-1\u00d727n+1  Applying law of indices (1/a = a-1)  3-5n \u00d7 32(n - 1) \u00d7 33n + 3  3-5n + 5n + 3 - 2 = 31=3","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>2>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : RATIO, PROPORTIONS AND RATES","question":"The sum of the ages of a woman and her daughter is 46 years. in 4 years time, the ratio of their ages will be 7:2  find their present ages    ** Leave your answer in whole number","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Take woman's age X  her daughter age by y    Sum of their present ages = X + y = 46 --------------eqn 1  Age of woman in four years = (x + 4)  Age of daughter in four years = (y + 4)    There the ratio is,  (x+4):(y+4)=72  cross-multiplying  2x + 8 = 7y + 28  2x - 7y = 20 ................ eqn 11    solving for both equations (1) and (11),  Multiply eqn (1) by 2,   We have,  2x + 2y = 92    substracting eqn (ii) from 2 x eqn (i), we have   2x + 2y = 92  2x - 7y = 20  9y = 72     Therefore,  y=729=8years  substitute y for 8 in eqn 1    x + 8 = 46  x = 46 - 8  x = 38 years    Therefore,  Woman's age = 38 years","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>3>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : FORMULATION AND EVALUATION OF ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES","question":"The sides of a rectangular floor are xm and (x+7)m. The diagonal is (x+8)m, calculate    The values of x     Leave your answer in whole number 'a'","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Diagram representing the Rectangular floor  Using pythagoras theorem,  x2 + (x + 7)2 = (x + 8)2  x2 + x2 + 14x + 49 = x2 + 16x + 64  2x2 + 14x + 49 - x2 - 16x - 64 = 0  x2 - 2x - 15 = 0  (x - 5)(x + 3) = 0  x = 5 or 3  It cannot be negative,  x = 5m","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>3>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : AREAS","question":"The sides of a rectangular floor are xm and (x+7)m. The diagonal is (x+8)m, calculate   The area of the floor     Leave your answer in whole number 'ab'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Area of floor = L \u00d7 B  A.o.F = (x + 7)(x) = x2 + 7x = 52 + 7(5)   25 + 35 = 60m2","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>4>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"The diagram above shows the bar charts representing the number of vehicles manufactured by a company in january, february and march, 1992    How many vehicles were produced in february     Leave your answer in whole number'ab'","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Looking at the bar chart,  Number of vehicles produced in february  40 + 25 + 30 = 95 vehicles","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>4>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : FRACTIONS, DECIMALS AND APPROXIMATIONS","question":"The diagram above shows the bar charts representing the number of vehicles manufactured by a company in january, february and march, 1992   what fraction of the vechicles manufactured in february were cars?     Leave your answer in fraction 'a/b'","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Fraction of vehicles that are cars   number of cars = 40  Fraction=4095=819","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>4>c","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"The diagram above shows the bar charts representing the number of vehicles manufactured by a company in january, february and march, 1992   How many buses were produced altogether from january to march,1992?    ** Leave your answer in whole number","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"From graph,  No of buses produced altogether are;  January = 20  February = 30  March = 50  adding up we have = 20 + 30 + 50 = 100 buses","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>4>d","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : RATIO, PROPORTIONS AND RATES","question":"The diagram above shows the bar charts representing the number of vehicles manufactured by a company in january, february and march, 1992   What is the ratio in lowest term of the number of lorries produced in february to that of march?     Leave your answer in ratio format 'a:b'","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"From the graph,  Lorries produced in february = 25  Lorries produced in March = 35  Ratio of Lorries  February : March = 25 : 35 = 5 : 7","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>5>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : ANGLES AND INTERCEPTS ON PARALLEL LINES","question":"In the diagram MN||ST, NP||QT and \u2220STQ = 70\u2218. find x      Leave your answer in whole number 'abc'","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Produce PN to meet ST at V           since NP is parallel QT  then  but  X = 180\u00b0 - 70\u00b0  X = 110\u00b0","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>5>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : ANGLES","question":"In the diagram above AC is a straight line, |BC\" = |BD|, BC\u0302D = 50\u2218and BA\u0302D =55\u2218 Find BD\u0302A      Leave your answer in whole number 'ab'","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The angle required (BDA)    Since \u0394BCD = Isosceles Triangle    155\u00b0 +","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>6>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : FUNCTIONS AND RELATIONS","question":"Draw the table of values for the relation y = x2 for the interval -3\u2264x\u22644","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Equation y = x2  Interval = -3 \u2264 x \u2264 4 i.e -3 to 4    Table One  x-3-2-101234y = x2941014916    Table Two  x-3-2-101234y = 2x + 3-3 -11357911","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>6>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : GRAPHS OF LINEAR AND QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS","question":"Using a scale of 2cm to rep 1unit on the x-axis and 2cm to rep 2 units on the y axis, draw the graphs of :    y = x2","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>6>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : GRAPHS OF LINEAR AND QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS","question":"Using a scale of 2cm to rep 1unit on the x-axis and 2cm to rep 2 units on the y axis, draw the graphs of :  y = 2x + 3 for -3\u2264x\u22644","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>6>c>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : QUADRATIC EQUATIONS","question":"Use your graph to find    The roots of the equation x2 = 2x+3","images":[],"marking_scheme":"From graph, the roots of x2 = 2x + 3 are x = -1 and x = 3 i.e points A an D","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>6>c>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : DRAWING TANGENTS TO CURVES TO DETERMINE THE GRADIENT AT A GIVEN POINT","question":"Use your graph to find   The gradient of y = x2 = -2     Leave your answer in whole number 'a'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Gradient of y = x2 ; x = -2  dydx=-82=-4","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>7>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"50 99 81 86 69 85 93 63 92  65   77 74 76 71 90 74 81 94 67 75   95 81 68 105 99 68 75 75 76 73   79 74 80 69 74 62 74 80 79 68   79 75 75 71 83 75 80 85 81 82    construct a frequency distribution table, using class interval 45-54, 54-64 e.t.c","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Class IntervalFrequencyTally45 - 54  55 - 64  65 - 74  75 - 84  85 - 94  95 - 104  105 - 1141  2  15  21  7  3  1I  II   IIII   IIII   IIII    IIII   IIII   IIII   IIII  I   IIII  II  III  I","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>7>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"50 99 81 86 69 85 93 63 92  65   77 74 76 71 90 74 81 94 67 75   95 81 68 105 99 68 75 75 76 73   79 74 80 69 74 62 74 80 79 68   79 75 75 71 83 75 80 85 81 82  Draw the histogram for the distribution","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>7>c","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"50 99 81 86 69 85 93 63 92  65   77 74 76 71 90 74 81 94 67 75   95 81 68 105 99 68 75 75 76 73   79 74 80 69 74 62 74 80 79 68   79 75 75 71 83 75 80 85 81 82  use your histogram for the distribution      Leave your answer in whole number 'ab'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"mode = 77 births (this is gotten from the graph)","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>7>d","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"50 99 81 86 69 85 93 63 92  65   77 74 76 71 90 74 81 94 67 75   95 81 68 105 99 68 75 75 76 73   79 74 80 69 74 62 74 80 79 68   79 75 75 71 83 75 80 85 81 82  calculate the mean number of births     Leave your answer in two decimal place 'ab.cd'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Class IntervalFrequencyTallyMid-point (x)Fx45 - 54  55 - 64  65 - 74  75 - 84  85 - 94  95 - 104  105 - 1141  2  15  21  7  3  1I  II   IIII   IIII   IIII    IIII   IIII   IIII   IIII  I   IIII  II  III  I49.5  59.5  69.5  79.5  89.5  99.5  109.549.5  119.0  1042.5  1669.5  626.5  298.5  109.5\u2211F = 50\u2211Fx = 3915.5    mean=\u2211Fx\u2211F=3915.550=78.31  Therefore, mean = 78.31","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>8>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : SETS","question":"In a market survey ,100 traders sell fruit, 40 sell apples, 46 oranges, 50 mangoes, 14 apples, 46 oranges,15 apples and mangoes  and 10 sell the three fruits. Each of the traders sell at least one of the three fruits    Represent the information in a venn diagram","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"From the survey, 100 fruit traders,  n = 100  n(apples) = n(A) = 40  n(orange) = n(R) = 46  n(mangoes) = n(M) = 50  n(Apples and oranges) = n(A \u2229 R) = 14   n(Apples and Mangoes) = n(A \u2229 M) = 15  n(A \u2229 R \u2229 M) = 10       5 +  10 + 4  + 9 = 40 ; 19 + a = 40 ;  a = 21  14 + x + b = 46 ; b = 35 - 2  15 + x + c = 50 ; c = 35 - x  Therefore  1 00 = 21 + 4 + 10 + 5 + x + 32 + x + 32 - x + 35 - x  100 = 107 - x , x = 7","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>8>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : SETS","question":"In a market survey ,100 traders sell fruit, 40 sell apples, 46 oranges, 50 mangoes, 14 apples, 46 oranges,15 apples and mangoes  and 10 sell the three fruits. Each of the traders sell at least one of the three fruits   Find the number that sell oranges and mangoes only.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"People that sell mangoes and oranges be,  (M \u2229 R) = X  Therefore, 10 traders sell all three fruits,  (M \u2229 R \u2229 A1) = X - 10  Therefore,   R \u2229 (A \u222a M)1 = 46 - (4 + 10 + x - 10) = 42 - X  M \u2229 (A \u222a R)1 = 50 - (5 + 10 + x - 10) = 45 - x  n(A \u222a R \u222a M) = 100  Therefore,  40 + (42 - X) + (45 - X) + (x - 10) = 100  117 - 100 = 17  X = 17  by substitution,  (M \u2229 R \u2229 A1) = 17 - 10 = 7  R \u2229 (A \u222a M)1 = 42 - 17 = 25  Therefore,  Those that sell oranges and Mangoes only are 25 and 28.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>8>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : NUMBER BASES","question":"Find the value of x for which 312four + 52x = 96ten     Leave your answer in whole number 'a'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"312four + 52x = 9610  expanding,  3 x 42 + 1 x 41 + 2 x 40 + 5 x x1 + 2 x x0 = 96  performing operations  48 + 4 + 2 + 5x + 2 = 96  5b + 5x = 96  Therefore,  5x = 96 - 56  5x = 40  dividing both sides by 5  x = 8","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>9>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CONSTRUCTION","question":"use a ruler and compass only.  construct quadrilateral MNOP with |OP| = 11cm, |PM| = 6cm, |ON| = 5cm, |MN| = 8cm  and 11cm, |PM| = 6cm, |ON| = 5cm  |MN| = 8cm and |MO|= 9cm","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>9>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CONSTRUCTION","question":"use a ruler and compass only.  construct quadrilateral MNOP with |OP| = 11cm, |PM| = 6cm, |ON| = 5cm, |MN| = 8cm  and 11cm, |PM| = 6cm, |ON| = 5cm  |MN| = 8cm and |MO|= 9cm   measure \u2220MPO","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Therefore,  Using a protractor,","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>9>c","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CONSTRUCTION","question":"use a ruler and compass only.  construct quadrilateral MNOP with |OP| = 11cm, |PM| = 6cm, |ON| = 5cm, |MN| = 8cm  and 11cm, |PM| = 6cm, |ON| = 5cm  |MN| = 8cm and |MO|= 9cm   Locate the point Y which is equidiatant from the striaght linees ON and OP and also equidistance from M and N","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>9>d","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CONSTRUCTION","question":"use a ruler and compass only.  construct quadrilateral MNOP with |OP| = 11cm, |PM| = 6cm, |ON| = 5cm, |MN| = 8cm  and 11cm, |PM| = 6cm, |ON| = 5cm  |MN| = 8cm and |MO|= 9cm   Draw  YP  and find the perimeter of \u2206OYP.     Leave your answer in one decimal place 'ab.c'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Perimeter of \u0394OYP  Perimeter is the sum of the three sides = 5.2cm + 8.6cm + 11cm = 24.8cm","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>10>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"The probability that three boys pass an examination are 2/3. 5/8 and 3/4 respectively. find the probability    all the three boys pass     Leave your answer in fraction 'a/b'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let the three boys be A, B and C  P(A)pass=23  P(B)pass=58  P(C)pass=34    Probability that A, B and C pass are   P(A) \u00d7 P(B) \u00d7 P(C)  23x58x34=516","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>10>a>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"The probability that three boys pass an examination are 2/3. 5/8 and 3/4 respectively. find the probability  none of the boys pass     Leave your answer in fraction 'a/b'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Probability that none of the boys pass  [1 - P(A)] x [1 - P(B)] x [1 - P(C)]  (1-23)(1-58)(1-34)  =13x38x14=132","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>10>a>iii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"The probability that three boys pass an examination are 2/3. 5/8 and 3/4 respectively. find the probability  only two of the boy pass     Leave your answer in fraction 'a/b'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Only two pass, the probability is;  A, B will pass and C failed  A, C will pass and B failed  B, C will pass and A failed    Therefore,  (23x58x14)+(23x34x38)+(58x34x13)  =548+316+532=215480=4396","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>10>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : PROFIT AND LOSS","question":"A shop-keeper marks a television set for sale at \u20a636,000 so as to makes a profit of 20% on the cost price, when he sells it,he allows a discount of 5% of the marked price. calculate the actual percentage profit.     Leave your answer in two decimal place 'ab.cd'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"%profit=profitcost price x 100   20=3600-x2x100  x = 30000  Discount  = 50% of 36000 ;  = 1800  now sellin price  = 36000 - 1800 = 34200  now profit = 34200 - 3000 = 4200  %profit=42003000x100  = 14%","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>11>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : QUADRATIC EQUATIONS","question":"The roots of the equation 2x2 +(p+1)x+q = 0 are 1 and 3, where p and q.      Leave your answer in this format 'p,q'","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"2x2 + (p + 1)x + q = 0  roots are 1 and 3  p and q are constants  sumofroots=-ba  Therefore, -(p+1)2=(1+3)-----------(i)  Productofroots=ca  Therefore, ca=q2=3x(1)--------------(ii)    From (i),  (p + 1) = 2(1 + 3)  p + 1 = -2(4)  p = -8 - 1 = -9  From (ii),  q = 3 x 2 = 6  q = 6","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2001>11>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2001","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : VARIATION","question":"The weight of an object varies inversely as the square of its distance from the centre of the earth.A Small satellite weight 80kg on the earth's surface . calculate, correct to nearest whole number, the weight of the satellite when it 800km above the surface of earth [Take the radius of the earth as 6,400km]","images":[],"marking_scheme":"wvarieswith1d2    w\u03b11d2  w=Rd2  801=R40,960,000  R = 80 \u00d7 40,960,000  R = 3,276,800,000  Therefore, substituting  w=3,276,800,000d2  when d = 800km above the surface  d = (6400 + 800)km = 7200km  w=3,276,800,000(7,200)2 = 63.2   \u2248 63kg","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"}];